Fireworks Popcorn! 🎆 Add Pop Rocks to create a poppin’ summer snack!

Ingredients:
🧨 Bag of popcorn (I used Skinny Pop)
🧨 White melting wafers, divided
🧨 Bag of cherry Pop Rocks
🧨 Festive sprinkles
🧨 Red, white and blue M&Ms
🧨 Blue food coloring

Steps:
1. Spread out popcorn on a baking sheet lined with parchment paper.
2. Melt 2/3 of the wafers per instructions, pour over popcorn and gently mix until evenly coated.
3. Top with Pop Rocks, sprinkles and M&Ms.
4. Melt the other 1/3 of wafers, mix in blue food coloring. Drizzle over popcorn. 
5. Allow to fully cool then serve!

Hot dog sliders, coming in HOT! Husband approved and an easy summer dinner idea!

Ingredients:
9 ct. slider rolls (such as King’s, do not pull apart)
6 hot dogs , sliced vertically in half
1 cup canned chili without beans
1 cup shredded cheddar cheese
2 tablespoons butter , melted
½ teaspoon poppy seeds
½ teaspoon onion powder

Instructions:
* Preheat oven to 350°F.
* Using a large bread knife, slice rolls in half horizontally so that you have one large top half and one large bottom half.  (Do not pull the rolls apart.)
* Place the bottom half of the rolls into a baking pan. Line hot dogs in single layer, then cover evenly with chili. Top with shredded cheese. Add top half of rolls.
* In a small bowl, combine melted butter with spices. Brush evenly over top of rolls.
* Cover with foil and bake 10 minutes, remove foil and bake another 10 minutes; until golden and heated through.
* Slice into individual sliders. Serve warm. 

Recipe inspired by Seeded at the Table

These Blueberry Star Shortcakes keep dessert simple so you can enjoy the fun summer nights. Cook blueberries on the stove. Use refrigerated biscuits, cut them into star shapes and top with sparkling sugar. Serve warm with whipped cream or ice cream for a fresh summer dessert!

Blueberry Star Shortcakes
4 cups fresh blueberries
1/2 cup granulated sugar
1 tsp lemon juice
1 can refrigerated buttermilk biscuits
Coarse sparkling sugar
Optional:  whipped cream and vanilla ice cream

1. Preheat oven according to biscuit package instructions. Combine first three ingredients in a medium saucepan, stirring often, until lightly bubbly and sugar dissolves. Remove from heat. 
2. Separate biscuits. Cut with a star-shaped cuter, place onto greased baking sheet and sprinkle with sparkling sugar. Bake biscuits according to package instructions or until lightly browned. 
3. Spoon blueberry mixture into individual bowls, top with biscuit. Serve while warm with whipped cream and ice cream, if desired.

🍎 Apple-Shaped Cookie Balls 🍎 Happy First Day of School to all those celebrating! Commemorating this special occasion with apple-shaped Oreo cookie balls!

Ingredients:
- Oreo cookies
- 8 ounce package of cream cheese, room temp
- Red melting chips
- Pretzel sticks
- Fresh mint, washed (can also use gummy spearmint leaves)

Steps:
- Crush 36 oreos in the food processor.
- Add Oreo crumbs to cream cheese and mix using a handheld mixer or paddle mixer until well blended.
- Shape mixture into balls and place on a cookie sheet lined with wax paper. Freeze for 20 minutes. 
- Place the red melting chips in a microwave-safe bowl and melt per package instructions.
- Dip each ball into the melting chips and place on the wax paper. Place half of a pretzel stick in the cookie ball to resemble an apple stem; top with a mint leaf. 
- Refrigerate for 30 minutes.

Heartbreak. With the heaviest of hearts we are devastated to share the loss of our son.  No one can prepare you for the weight of those two words, “I’m sorry.” The deep pain we have been walking through this past week has been filled with sorrow and coping with the fact that death is truly a thief.

What started out as a fun, routine 16 week checkup, turned into being unable to find his heartbeat, being escorted to the ultrasound room, talking with the doctor, and discussing operating room prep. It all happened in the span of about 15 minutes. I was numb. My body physically present but my eyes were visualizing a nightmare. My son was gone. Life can change so quickly and unexpectedly. 

Our son was and is lovingly referred to with the nickname “Buttons” while we decided on a formal name. He was tiny, but so important, and had the cutest button nose. We decided to formally name him Elijah - which means “the Lord is my God.” We know Elijah is in Heaven with Jesus and our loved ones. He was only with us for a short time but in those weeks I am grateful we made the most of it. We shared the life of Elijah with family and friends. He was celebrated. He was known. He was loved! Our son will always be a part of us. 

I know and trust God has a plan for our family. We have been showered with love from friends and family, and for that I am so grateful. Thank you. And a big thank you to my husband, Michael, you have been our rock through this storm. Our son will forever have a piece of our hearts. We are still in mourning, but on the road to recovery, physically and emotionally. The grief may linger but we hope to push towards finding light and joy in celebration of his life. 

In loving memory of our son,
Elijah “Buttons” Hoglan

Hugging this little one so tightly. 💕
We have witnessed an outpouring of love and support that has made this past week a little less sorrowful and a lot more hopeful. The best word I can describe this is kindness. 

- The kindness of God to welcome Elijah with open arms. He may have passed away on Earth but he was born into Heaven. 
- The kindness from friends, family and strangers for thoughts, prayers, and support. Thank you!
- The kindness from the doctors, nurses, medical staff, hospital chaplain and funeral home to offer comfort and empathy in this situation. 
- The kindness of sisterhood for reaching out and sharing stories of your own losses. I have been moved by your strength and am so grateful for the resources you have shared to help me grieve.
- The kindness of others, work and commitments for providing grace and space while we mourn. 

Can I tell you, the immense kindness of others changes things!!! It comforts us to know we have been lifted up by your prayers. We feel them! 

Our hearts are so grateful for the time we shared with Elijah and we will never stop thanking God for it! We hope to use this experience and pay this kindness forward to others. 
With love, hope and grace, 
The Hoglans

Tip:  How to see the best fall foliage, shared at the end 🍁 Visiting Stowe, VT, one of the most colorful places to travel in the fall!
A few of our favorite things:
- Walking around downtown Stowe, stop for coffee and their quaint bookshop. See the iconic church!
- Enjoy fresh apple cider and hot apple cider donuts.
- Drive up Mount Mansfield and hike along the trail for breathtaking views of fall foliage.
- Go on a scavenger hunt of covered bridges in the area to time travel back in history. 
- Discover the twists and turns of Smuggler’s Notch. There are a couple areas to stop and park to admire the canopy of leaves. 
- Indulge in pretzels and beer at the Von Trapp Brewery, I recommend making reservations in advance if you go during peak foliage season
- Use a map, like the New England fall foliage map, to pick your dates of travel based on peak foliage season

Pumpkin Spice Syrup
This recipe includes real pumpkin and all the autumn spice! Stir it into pumpkin spice lattes, pumpkin spice cold brew, pumpkin martinis or pumpkin spice oat milk shaken espressos. Drizzle it over pancakes, stir into oatmeal or pour over ice cream for delicious fall treats. This makes for a great gift for a friend! 

Pumpkin Spice Syrup 1/3 cup pumpkin
1/2 tsp cinnamon
1/2 tsp nutmeg
1/8 tsp cloves
1/2 tsp vanilla extract
1.5 cups coconut sugar
1 cup water
Put all ingredients in a sauce pan. Whisk together. Bring to a boil over medium heat. Reduce heat to a simmer for 10 minutes. Store in the refrigerator in an airtight container for up to a month. 
 Recipe from Kristin Cavallari

If videos could smell… this would be the smell of Christmas in a cozy house. I love a good simmer pot for relaxing on the weekends or celebrating in the holidays. This one embodies rich spices mixed with a little zest and will fill your home with festive cheer. 

Holiday Simmer Pot
1 orange, sliced
3/4 cups cranberries
1/2 cup mulling spices
2 sprigs rosemary or small branch from your live Christmas tree
8 cups water - optional to substitute half of the water with apple juice

Place all ingredients in a Dutch oven and stir to ensure all the dry ingredients are wet. Bring to a simmer. Allow to simmer uncovered for up to 2-3 hours. 

This holiday potpourri is perfect for hosting Thanksgiving, Christmas and holiday parties!

Decorating a mirror for Christmas 🎄 All supplies are in my LTK and stories. 

Decorating mirrors for the holidays is one of my favorite ways to add the Christmas spirit to my home and workspace. The best part is that you can make it your own using only a few supplies. Whether you prefer a traditional look with mixed greenery and bells, or a colorful party vibe with tinsel and blown ornaments, the possibilities are endless! 

My trick is to use strong vacuum suction hangers. These have two hooks each, perfect for layering garlands and adding other elements like lights, smaller string garlands, etc... They are quick to set up and easy to reposition/remove. I have them linked in my LTK. 

Steps:
– Clean mirror and allow to fully dry. – Place the suction hangers on the mirror towards the perimeter of the mirror. Follow suction hanger instructions to pull down lever to create a strong grip. Space hangers out, approximately one hanger every 1-2 feet. – Hang greenery garland along the hangers. (I used two strands of garland and had them overlapping for about a foot.) – Drape any finer garland or string lights, securing it on the hanger hooks.
– Place any desirable decorative objects near the mirror, like small trees, faux florals, etc…

Transform a store-bought cake into a winter wonderland cake. This was so fun, affordable and took under 10 minutes. 🎄❄️❤️

What I used:
- small vanilla celebration cake 
- gingerbread cookies (can sub with biscoffs)
- rosemary sprigs
